{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 16:23:38.103710", "event": "llm_start", "prompts": ["System: You are an expert network engineer.\nYour task is to submit the final solution for this network problem based on the diagnosis reported provided.\nCarefully review the diagnosis results and ensure that your submission is accurate and complete.\nYou must strictly follow the submission format and call the submit() tool to submit your solution.\nHuman: Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report\nNetwork / topology summary (relevant parts)\n- Two hosts: pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2/24) attached to leaf_router_0_0 (eth2: 10.0.0.1/24), and pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2/24) attached to leaf_router_0_1 (eth2: 10.0.1.1/24).\n- Two spines (spine_router_0_0 AS65100, spine_router_0_1 AS65101) peer with a super-spine (super_spine_router_0 AS65000) and with leaves.\n- Leaves are expected to advertise their /24 host subnets into EBGP to spines; spines should propagate them to super-spine and other spines.\n\nExecutive summary (high-level)\n- The network is partially functional: the 10.0.1.0/24 prefix (pc_0_1 / leaf_router_0_1) is being advertised and learned across the spines/super-spine.\n- The 10.0.0.0/24 prefix (pc_0_0 / leaf_router_0_0) is NOT visible outside leaf_router_0_0 — it is not present in spine or super-spine routing/BGP tables. As a result, other pods cannot reach 10.0.0.0/24.\n- Root cause: BGP neighbor configuration mismatch between the spines and leaf_router_0_0 (incorrect remote-AS configured on the spines for the leaf), causing the BGP sessions for that leaf to not form and the leaf’s prefix not to be propagated.\n- Secondary observation: pc_0_0 shows zero interface packet counters and active ping attempts to it from the test harness failed with \"Device ... is not running\" — indicating that the host may not be responsive/fully up. However, even if the host were up, the routing absence described above would prevent reachability from other pods.\n\nDetailed evidence and findings\n\n1) Host interface and traffic counters\n- pc_0_0:\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24\n  - RX packets 0  bytes 0, TX packets 0  bytes 0 (no observed traffic)\n  - ip route: default via 10.0.0.1\n- pc_0_1:\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.1.2/24\n  - RX packets 6 bytes 624, TX packets 6 bytes 476 (traffic seen)\n  - ip route: default via 10.0.1.1\n- leaf_router_0_0 eth2 (connected to pc_0_0): shows inet 10.0.0.1/24 but RX/TX packets are 0 — no traffic to/from that host was observed on the leaf.\n- leaf_router_0_1 eth2: shows packets (consistent with pc_0_1 traffic).\n\nInterpretation:\n- pc_0_0 (and its leaf-facing link) show no traffic; pc_0_1 and its leaf link show traffic. This suggests either pc_0_0 is down/unresponsive or traffic is not being forwarded/arriving. The ping tool attempts to reach pc_0_0 returned \"Device `10.0.0.2` is not running.\"\n\n2) BGP configuration mismatches (local config outputs)\n- leaf_router_0_0 configuration:\n  - \"router bgp 65800\" (leaf_0_0 AS = 65800)\n  - neighbors configured to spines: neighbor 172.16.0.4 remote-as 65100 and neighbor 172.16.0.8 remote-as 65101\n  - advertising network 10.0.0.0/24 locally\n- spine_router_0_0 configuration:\n  - \"router bgp 65100\"\n  - neighbors: neighbor 172.16.0.0 remote-as 65000, neighbor 172.16.0.5 remote-as 65200, neighbor 172.16.0.7 remote-as 65201\n    - Note: 172.16.0.5 is leaf_router_0_0's spine-facing IP, but spine expects that neighbor to be remote-as 65200 (NOT 65800).\n- spine_router_0_1 configuration:\n  - \"router bgp 65101\"\n  - neighbors: neighbor 172.16.0.2 remote-as 65000, neighbor 172.16.0.9 remote-as 65200, neighbor 172.16.0.11 remote-as 65201\n    - Note: 172.16.0.9 is leaf_router_0_0's other spine-facing IP, but spine expects remote-as 65200 (not 65800).\n\nConclusion from configs:\n- Both spine routers have an incorrect remote-as (65200) configured for the addresses that are actually leaf_router_0_0. leaf_router_0_0's AS is 65800. This AS mismatch will prevent BGP neighbor sessions from forming between the spines and leaf_router_0_0.\n\n3) BGP tables / route tables (selected outputs)\n- leaf_router_0_0 BGP table:\n  - Displays its local network: 10.0.0.0/24 (installed locally with next-hop 0.0.0.0).\n- spine_router_0_0 BGP / routing:\n  - BGP table shows only 10.0.1.0/24 (learned via 172.16.0.7 / leaf_router_0_1)\n  - ip route shows a route for 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.7; there is NO route for 10.0.0.0/24 on spine_router_0_0.\n- spine_router_0_1 BGP / routing:\n  - BGP table also shows 10.0.1.0/24 (learned via leaf_router_0_1); no 10.0.0.0/24 learned.\n- super_spine_router_0 BGP:\n  - Shows routes for 10.0.1.0/24 via its spine peers, but no 10.0.0.0/24.\n\nInterpretation:\n- 10.0.1.0/24 (leaf_router_0_1 → pc_0_1) propagated through spines and super-spine as expected; full visibility and typical path selection exist.\n- 10.0.0.0/24 (leaf_router_0_0 → pc_0_0) remains only local to leaf_router_0_0; it is not learned by spines or super-spine and therefore unreachable from other pods.\n\n4) Active ping tests from the test harness\n- Attempts to ping pc_0_0 and pc_0_1 via the provided ping tool failed with: \"Device `10.0.0.2` is not running.\" / \"Device `10.0.1.2` is not running.\"\n- The tool error suggests the test harness couldn't reach/execute pings on those device containers. This is a separate operational observation about the lab/test harness, but does not contradict the BGP observations.\n\nLocalization — which devices are implicated\n- Primary misconfiguration / fault devices:\n  - spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1: misconfigured remote-as for the neighbor IPs that correspond to leaf_router_0_0. This prevents the BGP sessions towards leaf_router_0_0 from establishing.\n  - Evidence: spine_router_0_0 config shows \"neighbor 172.16.0.5 remote-as 65200\" but leaf_router_0_0's AS is 65800. spine_router_0_1 shows \"neighbor 172.16.0.9 remote-as 65200\" but leaf_router_0_0 is AS65800.\n- Secondary / possibly affected device:\n  - pc_0_0: interface shows no packets and ping attempts reported \"Device ... is not running.\" It may be down/uninitialized inside the lab. Even if pc_0_0 were up, it would still be unreachable from the rest of the fabric due to the BGP propagation problem described above.\n\nRoot cause analysis (why reachability broken)\n- The immediate root cause: BGP neighbor AS mismatch between the spines and leaf_router_0_0. Because the spines are configured with the wrong remote-AS for leaf_router_0_0 (they expect AS65200), the EBGP sessions do not form. As a result leaf_router_0_0's advertised network 10.0.0.0/24 is not accepted/learned by the spine routers and therefore not propagated upward to super-spine nor sideways to other spines. This causes network-wide lack of visibility for 10.0.0.0/24.\n- The lack of traffic counters on pc_0_0 and on its leaf-facing interface is either a consequence of (a) the host is not up/inoperative, or (b) no traffic reaches the host because other routers do not have a route to its subnet. Both explanations fit the data; the BGP issue alone explains cross-pod reachability failure. The \"Device is not running\" ping-tool errors indicate the test harness could not interact with the host container.\n\nImpact statement\n- Cross-pod host reachability is asymmetric:\n  - pc_0_1 <-> pc_0_0: cannot reach 10.0.0.2 from the fabric because the route to 10.0.0.0/24 is missing from spines/super-spine.\n  - 10.0.1.0/24 (pc_0_1) is correctly propagated and reachable across the fabric.\n- Control-plane (BGP) visibility for leaf_router_0_0’s prefix is absent outside leaf_router_0_0, limiting any traffic destined to 10.0.0.0/24 from other pods.\n\nConfidence level\n- High confidence that the AS mismatch on spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1 for leaf_router_0_0 is the principal cause of the missing 10.0.0.0/24 propagation (directly evidenced by configs and the absence of the prefix in spine/super-spine BGP/routing tables).\n- Moderate confidence that pc_0_0 itself may be down/unresponsive — the lab’s ping tool reported the device not running and the interface counters on the host and leaf show zero traffic. This may be a separate problem or simply a symptom (traffic not arriving because of BGP).\n\nKey artifacts / excerpts (evidence pointers)\n- leaf_router_0_0 BGP AS: \"router bgp 65800\" and \"network 10.0.0.0/24\" (leaf is advertising 10.0.0.0 locally).\n- spine_router_0_0 config: \"neighbor 172.16.0.5 remote-as 65200\" (incorrect remote-as for leaf_router_0_0 which is AS 65800).\n- spine_router_0_1 config: \"neighbor 172.16.0.9 remote-as 65200\" (same incorrect remote-as).\n- spine BGP / routing: spines show 10.0.1.0/24 in their BGP table and routes; there is no 10.0.0.0/24 present on spines or super-spine.\n- Interface counters: pc_0_0 eth0 RX/TX = 0; leaf_router_0_0 eth2 RX/TX = 0. pc_0_1 and leaf_router_0_1 show traffic.\n- Ping tool errors: \"Device `10.0.0.2` is not running.\" / \"Device `10.0.1.2` is not running.\" (test harness-level observation).\n\nSummary / final statement\n- The primary anomaly is that leaf_router_0_0’s prefix (10.0.0.0/24) is not propagated beyond the leaf because BGP sessions between that leaf and both spine routers are not established due to misconfigured remote-AS values on the spine routers. This prevents cross-pod reachability to pc_0_0. Additionally, pc_0_0 shows no traffic and the test harness could not reach the device, so the host may also be offline; however even a live host would be unreachable from other pods until the BGP control-plane issue is resolved.\n\n(End of diagnostic report — no mitigation steps provided per request.), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.\nAI: \nTool: [\"dns_record_error\", \"host_crash\", \"host_ip_conflict\", \"host_incorrect_dns\", \"host_incorrect_gateway\", \"host_incorrect_ip\", \"host_incorrect_netmask\", \"host_missing_ip\", \"dhcp_service_down\", \"dns_service_down\", \"host_vpn_membership_missing\", \"link_detach\", \"link_down\", \"link_flap\", \"link_fragmentation_disabled\", \"arp_acl_block\", \"bgp_acl_block\", \"dns_port_blocked\", \"http_acl_block\", \"icmp_acl_block\", \"ospf_acl_block\", \"bgp_asn_misconfig\", \"bgp_blackhole_route_leak\", \"bgp_hijacking\", \"bgp_missing_route_advertisement\", \"host_static_blackhole\", \"dhcp_missing_subnet\", \"mac_address_conflict\", \"ospf_area_misconfiguration\", \"ospf_neighbor_missing\", \"p4_aggressive_detection_thresholds\", \"flow_rule_loop\", \"flow_rule_shadowing\", \"sdn_controller_crash\", \"southbound_port_block\", \"southbound_port_mismatch\", \"p4_header_definition_error\", \"p4_compilation_error_parser_state\", \"mpls_label_limit_exceeded\", \"p4_table_entry_misconfig\", \"p4_table_entry_missing\", \"bmv2_switch_down\", \"frr_service_down\", \"arp_cache_poisoning\", \"dhcp_spoofed_dns\", \"dhcp_spoofed_gateway\", \"web_dos_attack\", \"link_bandwidth_throttling\", \"link_high_packet_corruption\", \"link_queue_overflow\", \"dns_lookup_latency\", \"load_balancer_overload\"]\nAI: \nTool: Submission success."], "metadata": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 16:23:42.729275", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Thanks — the diagnosis report was clear.\n\nI have submitted the solution with:\n- is_anomaly: true\n- faulty_devices: [\"spine_router_0_0\", \"spine_router_0_1\", \"pc_0_0\"]\n- root_cause_name: [\"bgp_asn_misconfig\", \"host_crash\"]\n\nRecommended immediate fixes (summary you can apply)\n- On spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1: correct the remote-as for the neighbor IPs corresponding to leaf_router_0_0 to remote-as 65800 (matching leaf_router_0_0's AS). This will allow EBGP sessions to form and the 10.0.0.0/24 prefix to be propagated.\n- On pc_0_0: verify the host/container is running and properly initialized. If necessary, restart the host/container so its interface comes up and begins sending/receiving traffic.\n\nIf you want, I can generate the exact commands/config snippets to apply to the spine routers and steps to verify BGP session establishment and route propagation.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 3434, "output_tokens": 226, "total_tokens": 3660, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 2688}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 0}}}
